ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Comprehensive explanation of the stepwise development of the revised Animal Epidemic Prevention Law and background on the revisions included, published after the final endorsement of its 3rd draft by the National People's Congress of the People's Republic of China, is available (in Chinese) at http://www.npc.gov.cn/wszb/zb14/zzzb14.shtml.

The following selected 3 explanatory notes are available at http://www.npc.gov.cn/npc/dwfyfxdca003/202101/5d4958df985f44a88b7de48639d44b21.shtml:

1. In order to make it more clear that the degree of harm to human health and the degree of economic loss and social impact of animal diseases are used as the basis for the classification of animal diseases, the 3rd review draft has been revised to classify animal diseases into "particularly serious harm to humans and animals," "serious hazards," and "hazards," as well as, in relation to economic loss and social impact, "significant," "larger," and "a certain degree," are used as the basis for the classification of animal diseases into the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd categories.

2. The lack of relevant quarantine regulations is a shortcoming in the current work on the prevention and control of wild animal epidemics. The 3rd review draft adds relevant provisions: The State Council's agricultural and rural administrative department, together with the State Council's wildlife protection department, formulates wild animal quarantine measures.

3. Animal epidemic prevention work should focus on the role of social forces. The 3rd review draft adds regulations to encourage and support practicing veterinarians, rural veterinarians, animal diagnosis and treatment institutions, and related enterprises to carry out animal epidemic prevention and provide epidemic prevention services.

The full revised text of the Animal Epidemic Prevention Law (in Chinese), which will take effect on 1 May 2021, is available at https://tinyurl.com/y5ror2ye (An official English version is expected to become available later).

Additional information is available at https://npcobserver.com/legislation/animal-epidemic-prevention-law/.

China's revisions in the relevant legislation are a step forward; however, and as expressed in some views presented in the above Guardian report, China's attempts to prevent another zoonotic disease outbreak will fail without deep changes in enforcement, oversight, extensive investment, and the involvement of local governments (municipal veterinary units) to ramp up veterinary capacity. - Mod.AS

